## 1. Overview & Core Concepts

This microservice is the **intelligent intermediary** between your domain applications and one or more LLM providers. It is designed as a **generic, async pipeline-based platform** — rule refinement is the first pipeline, with the architecture ready to host any number of LLM workflows without structural change.

### What a Checkpoint Is

> A **Checkpoint** is a named **data quality standard** that an ingested rule is evaluated against **before** it reaches the LLM refinement stage. Checkpoints are declarative JSON specifications — non-developers can author and manage them without writing Python.

Checkpoints answer: *“Does this rule meet the required standards before we ask the LLM to refine it?”*

If a rule fails one or more checkpoints, the failures are compiled into a structured feedback payload and passed directly into the LLM refinement prompt so the model knows exactly what to fix.

### Checkpoint Scopes

|Scope            |Description                               |Example                                      |
|-----------------|------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------|
|**Generic**      |Global quality gates applied to every rule|Min length, no placeholder text              |
|**Enterprise**   |Standards owned by enterprise governance  |Regulatory language, mandatory clauses       |
|**Domain / LOB** |Standards for a specific business domain  |Domain terminology, required field references|
|**Rule-specific**|Overrides tied to one particular rule     |Custom constraint for a legacy rule          |

### Python vs Java — Key Differences in This Design

|Concern             |Java Approach                     |Python Approach                                                   |
|--------------------|----------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|
|Concurrency         |Virtual Threads (Project Loom)    |`asyncio` + `async/await` throughout                              |
|Immutable records   |Java `record`                     |Pydantic `BaseModel` with `model_config = ConfigDict(frozen=True)`|
|Dependency injection|Spring `@Component` / `@Autowired`|`dependency-injector` library or FastAPI `Depends()`              |
|ORM                 |Spring Data JPA                   |SQLAlchemy 2.x async with `AsyncSession`                          |
|DB migrations       |Flyway                            |Alembic                                                           |
|Templating          |Mustache                          |Jinja2                                                            |
|LLM abstraction     |Spring AI                         |LiteLLM (multi-provider) or LangChain                             |
|Schema validation   |Bean Validation + Jackson         |Pydantic v2                                                       |
|Testing             |JUnit 5 + WireMock                |Pytest + `respx` (async HTTP mocking)                             |

